[1] Romania (Braila), 4th outbreak
Date: Sun 4 Dec 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters alertnet, 4 Dec 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L04719969.htm>

Deadly strain seen in new Romania bird flu cases
-----------------------------------------------
Romania will send samples from new cases of bird flu detected in the
southeast of the country for testing in Britain next week, but
officials said on Sunday [4 Dec 2005] the birds had most likely
contracted the deadly H5N1 strain.
Late on Saturday [3 Dec 2005] the H5 strain of the virus was found in
poultry in the village of Ciocile outside the Danube delta, where the
highly pathogenic H5N1 strain was 1st discovered in October 2005, and
culling of over 8000 birds started. [Ciocile, the 4th infected site
in Braila, is situated at the southwestern tip of the county; see map at
<http://www.aboutromania.com/Braila.gif>. - Mod.AS]
"We are almost sure it's the N1 subtype, taking into account what
we've seen so far in Romania," Gabriel Predoi, a top official from
the national Animal Health Agency, told Reuters.
Predoi said officials would send the Ciocile samples to a laboratory
in Britain next week [3rd week December 2005] to be absolutely sure
it was the deadly strain.
TV images showed pictures of masked men in white overalls catching
and culling hens, ducks and geese in Ciocile, which was quarantined,
while local people watched, some with tears in their eyes.
Disinfection filters were installed on all roads leading out of the
county of Braila, home to Ciocile and 3 other villages where the
virus was detected over the past week.
Officials said all the outbreaks occurred in villages close to lakes
where migratory birds often rest. They repeated recommendations that
people keep their flocks isolated so they do not come into contact
with wild birds.
Veterinary inspectors stepped up testing and controls to ensure that
villagers abide by the recommendations in the area affected and in
neighboring counties.
In October 2005, the Balkan state became the 1st country in mainland
Europe to detect the deadly H5N1 virus in poultry in 2 villages in
the Danube delta, Europe's largest wetlands near the Black Sea.
The 1st bird flu case outside the delta occurred on 26 Nov 2005 in
the village of Scarlatesti, close to Ciocile and about 70 miles (110
km) from the delta.
Romania has not reported any cases of bird flu in humans so far.
--
